<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note42" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref42
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">42</A>
His full name was
	<A HREF="
E/Gazetteer/Places/Europe/Italy/Lazio/Roma/Rome/museums/Museo_Nazionale_Romano/Palazzo_Altemps/inscriptions/Vettius_Praetextatus.html
	"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(EClickHere+'an interesting inscription in honor of this man, with some further commentary.<BR><I>(Opens in another window)</I>')"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Vettius Agorius Praetextatus</A>. He appears as prefect of the city in
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/27*.html#9.8
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<SPAN CLASS="small">XXVII</SPAN>.9.8</A>, and
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/28*.html#1.24
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<SPAN CLASS="small">XXVIII</SPAN>.1.24</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note43" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref43
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">43</A>
<I>Cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Claudian/In_Eutropium/1*.html#58
	"TARGET="Claudian_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EPlusL,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Claudian, <I>In Eutr.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">I</SPAN>.59</A>, <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">hinc fora venalis Galata ductore frequentat permutatque domos varias</SPAN> (<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Eutropius</SPAN>), "next in the train of a Galatian slave-merchant he stands for sale in many a market and knows many diverse houses"
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Claudian/In_Eutropium/1*.html#58
	"TARGET="Claudian_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EPlusL,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(<I>L. C. L.</I>, <SPAN CLASS="small">I</SPAN>, p143)</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note44" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref44
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">44</A>
The Divi, or Diveni, lived on some island off the west coast of India, the Serendivi probably on the island of Ceylon, called <SPAN CLASS="archaic">Serandib</SPAN> by the Arabs. Gibbon says that these embassies were not due to Julian's widespread fame, since they must have thought that Constantius was still ruling. So also Zonaras, <SPAN CLASS="small">XIII</SPAN>.12.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note45" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref45
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">45</A>
See
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/20*.html#note61
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<SPAN CLASS="small">XX</SPAN>.8.4, note</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note46" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref46
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">46</A>
Ammianus' account is confused and in places inaccurate.

	<DIV CLASS="mynote">
	<P CLASS="b0 a0">
Thayer's Note: For a detailed look at just how, see
	<A HREF="
http://research.ncl.ac.uk/histos/documents/1998.11DrijversAmmianusonPontusEuxinus268278.pdf
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
J. W. Drijvers, "Ammianus Marcellinus on the Geography of the Pontus Euxinus" (Histos <SPAN CLASS="small">II</SPAN>, 1998)</A>.
	</DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note47" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref47
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">47</A>
Modern <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">Ἱερὸν Ὄρος</SPAN>, Monte Santo.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note48" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref48
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">48</A>
Under Xerxes: see
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/7B*.html#122
	"TARGET="Herodotus_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Herodotus,WIDTH,220)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Hdt. <SPAN CLASS="small">VII</SPAN>.122</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note49" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref49
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">49</A>
Its mediaeval name was Negroponte and the headland's Cappo<A CLASS="comment"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('(sic)',WIDTH,60)"
onMouseOut="nd();">º</A> d'Oro.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note50" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref50
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">50</A>
In order to avenge the death of his son, Nauplius kindled a beacon-fire on the cliff, which misled the Greek fleet and caused its almost utter destruction.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note51" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref51
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">51</A>
This is not accurate, but makes the Aegean and the Thessalian sea, more commonly called <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Mare Thracicum</SPAN>, too large; see Strabo, Mela, and Pliny.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note52" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref52
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">52</A>
Looking eastward.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note53" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref53
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">53</A>
Apollo and Diana.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note54" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref54
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">54</A>
<I>Cf.</I> <A HREF="
http://www.thelatinlibrary.com/horace/carm1.shtml
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(EClickHere+'Horace\'s <I>Odes</I>, Book 1'+Lat2+LatSearch+'retortis</SPAN>',WIDTH,185)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Hor., <I>Odes</I>, <SPAN CLASS="small">I</SPAN>.2.13</A>, <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">retortis violenter undis</SPAN>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note55" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref55
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">55</A>
On Tenedos: <I>Iliad</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">I</SPAN>.38;
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/13A*.html#1.46
	"TARGET="Strabo_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Strabo,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Strabo, <SPAN CLASS="small">XIII</SPAN>.1.46</A>. The god has this epithet from <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">σμίνθος</SPAN>, a kind of field-mouse destructive to the crops, destroyed by Apollo.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note56" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref56
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">56</A>
The Bay of Saros, west of the Thracian Chersonese and the Hellespont.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note57" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref57
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">57</A>
According to the myth, he fed his horses on human flesh, and was slain by Hercules.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note58" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref58
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">58</A>
To‑day the Maritza.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note59" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref59
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">59</A>
Modern Marogna. The identification of this town with the city founded by Aeneas in Thrace is doubtful, since Homer says that auxiliaries came from there to Ilium, and Apollodorus represents Heracles as landing there on his return from Troy; see Heyne, <I>Excursus to Aen. <SPAN CLASS="small">III</SPAN></I> p416; and
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/28*.html#4.13
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<SPAN CLASS="small">XXVIII</SPAN>.4.13, below</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note60" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref60
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">60</A>
This seems to refer to the Propontis; see
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#8.6
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
§ 6, below</A>. This part of the description looks hopelessly confused; Ammianus returns to Aenos or farther westward; see
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#note72
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
note 2, p218</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note61" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref61
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">61</A>
<SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">Κυνὸς σῆμα</SPAN>, "the dog's monument," since Hecuba, after the capture of Troy, was said to have been changed into a dog; <I>cf.</I> <A HREF="
http://www.thelatinlibrary.com/ovid/ovid.met13.shtml
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(EClickHere+'Book 13<BR>of Ovid\'s <I>Metamorphoses</I>'+Lat2+LatSearch+'clarique</SPAN>',WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Ovid, <I>Metam.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">XIII</SPAN>.399 ff.</A>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note62" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref62
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">62</A>
Gallipoli.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note63" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref63
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">63</A>
See
	<A HREF="
http://www.thelatinlibrary.com/nepos/nepos.them.shtml
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(EClickHere+'Nepos\' Life of Themistocles'+Lat2+LatSearch+'Lampsacum</SPAN>',WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Nepos, <I>Them.</I> 10.3</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note64" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref64
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">64</A>
The Sea of Marmora.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note65" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref65
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">65</A>
On the southern side of the Propontis.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note66" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref66
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">66</A>
Named from Mt. Dindymus, in Phrygia, near Pessinus. There is another Mt. Dindymus, five miles north of Cyzicus, and, apparently, a town or village called Dindyma.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note67" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref67
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">67</A>
Cybele.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note68" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref68
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">68</A>
There is evidently a lacuna here. Lindenbrog suggested <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">ubi Hylam insecuta rapuit nympha</SPAN>. Others refer Hyla to the river near Cius.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note69" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref69
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">69</A>
Nicomedia.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note70" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref70
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">70</A>
<I>Cf.</I> <A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Pliny_the_Elder/2*.html#149
	"TARGET="Pliny"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Pliny,WIDTH,205)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Pliny, <I>N. H.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">II</SPAN>.149</A>;
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/7Fragments*.html#55.5
	"TARGET="Strabo_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Strabo,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Strabo, <SPAN CLASS="small">VII</SPAN>.55 (<SPAN CLASS="small">III</SPAN>.377, <I>L. C. L.</I>)</A>. It was also famous as the scene of the last battle of the Peloponnesian war.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note71" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref71
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">71</A>
See
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#8.4
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
§ 4, above</A>, and the note.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note72" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref72
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">72</A>
This island is a long way to the westward of the middle of the Propontis, and since the length of the two islands is from west to east, they would form a theta, <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">Θ</SPAN>, rather than a <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">Φ</SPAN>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note73" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref73
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">73</A>
Here the reference clearly is to the whole of the Propontis.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note74" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref74
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">74</A>
Modern Scutari, opposite Constantinople.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note75" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref75
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">75</A>
According to the Eusebian Chronicle, Byzantium was founded by the Megarians in Olymp. 30, 2 (600 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>);


<A ID="p219x"></A>so also Herodotus
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/4F*.html#144
	"TARGET="Herodotus_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Herodotus,WIDTH,220)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(<SPAN CLASS="small">IV</SPAN>.144)</A>, who, however, gives the date as Olym. 26, 2 (616 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>). Justin
	<A HREF="
https://www.forumromanum.org/literature/justin/texte9.html#1
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2PlusTranslation,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(<SPAN CLASS="small">IX</SPAN>.1.2 f.)
	</A>
names the Spartans; Velleius
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Velleius_Paterculus/2A*.html#7.7
	"TARGET="Velleius_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EPlusL,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(<SPAN CLASS="small">II</SPAN>.7.7)
	</A>
the Milesians, who were descended from the Athenians. The founding was probably attributed to the Athenians from the time of Constantine from motives of pride.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note76" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref76
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">76</A>
A pharos, or lighthouse.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note77" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref77
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">77</A>
The Pontus, or Euxine Sea.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note78" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref78
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">78</A>
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Polybius/4*.html#39
	"TARGET="Polybius_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Polybius,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Polyb. <SPAN CLASS="small">IV</SPAN>.39.1</A>, gives 20,000;
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/2E2*.html#5.22.6
	"TARGET="Strabo_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Strabo,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Strabo, <SPAN CLASS="small">II</SPAN>.5.22</A>,<A CLASS="correction"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('The Loeb edition<BR>omits '+SearchF+'.22'+CloseF+'',WIDTH,120)"
onMouseOut="nd();">º</A> 25,000;
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Pliny_the_Elder/4*.html#77
	"TARGET="Pliny"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Pliny,WIDTH,205)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Pliny, <I>N. H.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">IV</SPAN>.77</A>, says that Varro made it 21,000, and Nepos, 21,350.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note79" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref79
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">79</A>
The descriptions of the Scythian bow in the handbooks on antiquities vary, and are sometimes misleading, in particular the comparison with different forms of the Greek sigma. As represented in vases and other works of art, it has, as a general rule, the form of the following cut:

<DIV ALIGN="center">
	<TABLE CLASS="basicH aqua image">
		<TR><TD><IMG TITLE="" WIDTH="567" HEIGHT="100" SRC="
Images/Gazetteer/Periods/Roman/Topics/Warfare/weapons/arcus/1A*.gif
		" ALT="
[image ALT: A woodcut of an unstrung bow.]
		"></TD></TR>
	</TABLE>
</DIV>

	<P CLASS="justify">
from
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/secondary/SMIGRA*/Arcus2.html#wcut.1
	"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Smith's <I>Dict. of Ant.</I><SPAN CLASS="superscript">1</SPAN>, p126</A>. It is well defined in
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/2E2*.html#ref187
	"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
the note on Strabo, <SPAN CLASS="small">II</SPAN>.5.22, in <I>L. C. L.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">I</SPAN>.479, n4</A>. When


<A ID="p221x"></A>it was drawn, which is commonly taken to be the meaning of <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">nervo coagmentati</SPAN>, the arms were bent down and the handle remained immovable; see also
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#note116
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
note on § 37, below</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note80" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref80
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">80</A>
The Palus Maeotis is on the northern side of the Euxine.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note81" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref81
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">81</A>
The directions are so uncertain that the meaning it is not clear.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note82" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref82
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">82</A>
<I>Cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/5C*.html#76
	"TARGET="Herodotus_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Herodotus,WIDTH,220)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Hdt. <SPAN CLASS="small">V</SPAN>.76</A>;
	<A HREF="
