"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">162</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Pietas tua</SPAN> is one of the numerous titles by which the later emperors were addressed.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note163" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref163
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">163</A>
With the expression <I>cf.</I> Caesar (<SPAN CLASS="small italic">ap.</SPAN> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Gellius/1*.html#10.4
	"TARGET="Gellius_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EPlusL,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Gell. <SPAN CLASS="small">I</SPAN>.10.4</A>), <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">ut tamquam scopulum fugias . . . insolens verbum</SPAN>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note164" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref164
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">164</A>
The sign either of military rank or of a position at court; the right to wear it was lost with the office.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note165" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref165
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">165</A>
This seems to be a sarcastic reference to the "muck-raking" that would characterize the trial.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note166" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref166
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">166</A>
Astraea, who left the earth in the iron age; <I>cf.</I> <A HREF="
http://www.thelatinlibrary.com/ovid/ovid.met1.shtml
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(EClickHere+'Book 1<BR>of Ovid\'s <I>Metamorphoses</I>'+Lat2+LatSearch+'iacet</SPAN>',WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Ovid., <I>Metam.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">I</SPAN>.150 f.</A>, <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Victa iacet pietas et virgo caede madentes Ultima caelestum terras Astraea reliquit</SPAN>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note167" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref167
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">167</A>
That is, was represented by Aratus, a Greek poet of Soli in Cilicia (<I>circ.</I> 276 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>), as leaving the earth; <I>cf.</I> Aratus, 130, <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">καὶ τότε μισήσασα δίκη κείνων γένος ἀνδρῶν ἕπταθ’ ὑπουρανίη</SPAN>: Cic., <I>Arat. Phaen.</I> 137 ff. (lines 1, 3 and 4 in the supplement of Grotius):

<DIV ALIGN="center"><TABLE CLASS="Latin verse">
	<TR>
		<TD>
			<P>
Tunc, mortale exosa genus, dea in alta volavit
			<P>
Et Iovis in regno caelique in parte resedit,
			<P>
Illustrem sortita locum, qua nocte serena
			<P>
Virgo conspicuo fulget vicina Boötae.
		</TD>
	</TR>
</TABLE></DIV>

	<DIV CLASS="mynote">
	<P CLASS="b0 a0">
Thayer's Note: Not only Aratus; see
	<A HREF="
E/Gazetteer/Topics/astronomy/_Texts/secondary/ALLSTA/Virgo*.html#Justice
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Allen's <I>Star Names</I>, <I>s.v.</I> <SPAN CLASS="smallcaps">Virgo</SPAN></A>.
	</DIV>


