E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref197
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">197</A>
Diocletian had done the same in his edict, <I>De Pretiis Venalium Rerum</I>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note198" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref198
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">198</A>
This work has survived. It means "<I>The Beard-Hater</I>"; see Julian, <I>L. C. L.</I>, <SPAN CLASS="small">II</SPAN>.420 ff. It is a satire on Julian himself, in which he also scolded the people of Antioch. They made fun of his beard because they themselves were clean-shaven. Hadrian and his successors wore beards, but Constantine and his successors did not.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note199" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref199
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">199</A>
One of a people living in an island near Sicily, changed by Jupiter into apes;
	<A HREF="
http://www.thelatinlibrary.com/ovid/ovid.met14.shtml
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(EClickHere+'Book 14<BR>of Ovid\'s <I>Metamorphoses</I>'+Lat2+LatSearch+'Cercopum</SPAN>',WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Ov., <I>Metam.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">XIV</SPAN>.91</A>, and Suidas, <I>s.v.</I> <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">Κέρκωπες</SPAN>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
