<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note242" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref242
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">242</A>
Described in
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/17*.html#4.8
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<SPAN CLASS="small">XVII</SPAN>.4.8 ff.</A>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note243" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref243
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">243</A>
Modern Assouan.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note244" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref244
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">244</A>
That is, they cast no shadows. Macrobius, <I>Somn. Scip.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">II</SPAN>.7.15<!--</A>MACROBIUS:SOMNIUM-->, limits this to <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">eo die quo sol certam partem ingreditur


<A ID="p295x"></A>Cancri, hora dies sexta</SPAN>; Strabo also limits the time to midday
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/17A3*.html#1.48
	"TARGET="Strabo_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Strabo,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(<SPAN CLASS="small">XVII</SPAN>.1.48; <I>L. C. L.</I>, <SPAN CLASS="small">VIII</SPAN> p129)</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note245" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref245
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">245</A>
From <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">ἀντί</SPAN>, "against," "opposite, and <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">σκιά</SPAN>, "shadow." Ammianus means that the locality is so far south that the sun for a time casts shadows southwards; <I>cf.</I> <A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Pliny_the_Elder/2*.html#183
	"TARGET="Pliny"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Pliny,WIDTH,205)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Pliny, <I>N. H.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">II</SPAN>.183</A>, <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">per eos dies <SPAN CLASS="small">XC</SPAN> in meridiem umbras iaci</SPAN>, "the shadows are turned towards the south."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify" ID="note246">
	<A CLASS="note" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref246a
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">246a</A>
	<A CLASS="note" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref246b
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">246b</A>
<I>I.e.</I> Antinoü(polis), also called Antinupolis (see
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/18*.html#9.1
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<SPAN CLASS="small">XVIII</SPAN>.9.1</A>). Antinupolis was not actually founded by Hadrian, but he embellished<A CLASS="correction"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('The Loeb edition<BR>has '+BadF+'enbellished'+CloseF+'',WIDTH,120)"
onMouseOut="nd();">º</A> and renamed it.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note247" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref247
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">247</A>
<I>Cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/17*.html#4.2
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><SPAN CLASS="small">XVII</SPAN>.4.2</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note248" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref248
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">248</A>
All other writers say that Peleus was banished by his father Aeacus, and fled to Eurytus, son of Actor, who purified him; <I>cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Diodorus_Siculus/4D*.html#72.6
	"TARGET="Diodorus_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Diodorus,WIDTH,185)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Diod. Sic. <SPAN CLASS="small">IV</SPAN>.72.6</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note249" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref249
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">249</A>
Also called Casium and containing a temple of Jupiter Casius. He was also worshipped in Syria; <I>cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#14.4
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">14.4, above</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note250" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref250
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">250</A>
<I>Cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/4G*.html#150
	"TARGET="Herodotus_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Herodotus,WIDTH,220)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Hdt. <SPAN CLASS="small">IV</SPAN>.150 ff.</A>;
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/17C*.html#3.21
	"TARGET="Strabo_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Strabo,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Strabo, <SPAN CLASS="small">XVII</SPAN>.3.21</A>. The founder is sometimes called Aristaeus
	<A HREF="
https://www.forumromanum.org/literature/justin/texte13.html#7
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2PlusTranslation,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(Just. <SPAN CLASS="small">XIII</SPAN>.7.1)</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note251" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref251
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">251</A>
Because of its importance as a grain supply; <I>cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Julius*.html#35
	"TARGET="Suetonius_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EPlusL,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Suet. <I>Jul.</I> 35.1</A>;
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Tacitus/Histories/1A*.html#11
	"TARGET="Tacitus_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Tacitus,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Tac. <I>Hist.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">I</SPAN>.11</A>. The <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">praefectus Aegypti</SPAN> ranked next to the <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">praefectus praetorio</SPAN> in the equestrian <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">cursus honorum</SPAN>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note252" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref252
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">252</A>
<I>Cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/17A1*.html#1.6
	"TARGET="Strabo_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Strabo,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Strabo, <SPAN CLASS="small">XVII</SPAN>.1.6 (at end)</A>;
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Alexander*/4.html#26.5
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Plutarch, <I>Alex.</I> 26.5 f.</A>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note253" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref253
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">253</A>
The pharos was the work of Sostrates of Cnidus, master-builder of Ptolemy Philadelphus. It was destroyed during the Alexandrine war, and rebuilt by Cleopatra.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note254" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref254
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">254</A>
It was built on an island called Pharos; its height is estimated to have been about 360 feet, and its base 82 feet square. It stood until 1477 or 1478, when a fort was built from its material.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note255" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref255
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">255</A>
A causeway seven stadia in length; "it is now, generally speaking, a mile wide, and forms a large part of the


<A ID="p301x"></A>site of the modern city"
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/17A1*.html#note35
	"TARGET="Strabo_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Strabo,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(Strabo, <I>L. C. L.</I>, vol. <SPAN CLASS="small">VIII</SPAN> p27, n2</A>.<A CLASS="comment"
onMouseOver="return Ebox('(Sic. Not an accurate quote, and the note number in the print edition is '+SearchF+'e'+CloseF+'.)')"
onMouseOut="nd();">º</A> <I>Cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/17A1*.html#1.6
	"TARGET="Strabo_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Strabo,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Strabo, <SPAN CLASS="small">XVII</SPAN>.1.6 (p792)</A>. This also is earlier than Cleopatra.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note256" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref256
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">256</A>
<I>Odyss.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">IV</SPAN>.400 ff.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note257" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref257
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">257</A>
The language is somewhat obscure, but the meaning is clear. The Heptastadion connected the island of Pharos with the mainland, and so took away the right of the Rhodians to tax it as an island.<!-- zzz: This is very similar to the story of Captain Streeter in Chicago; explain and link here if I ever put up a serious Streeterville site. (<SPAN CLASS="whole">scholar</SPAN>&shy;ly source: Journal of the Illinois State Historical Society, 13(4):571‑574 January, 1921) -->


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note258" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref258
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">258</A>
Ammianus confuses two libraries, that of the Bruchion and that of the Serapeum. The former was founded by Ptolemy Soter (322‑283 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>) and in the time of Callimachus contained 490,000 volumes; the Serapeum, founded by Ptolemy Philadelphus (285‑247 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>), contained 42,800. At the time of the battle of Pharsalia the total number was 532,800 and it may have reached 700,000 by the time of the Alexandrine war. Antony gave Cleopatra 200,000 volumes that had been collected in Pergamum. The damage done


<A ID="p303x"></A> by Caesar has been greatly exaggerated. Strabo, who visited Alexandria <SPAN CLASS="whole">twenty-three</SPAN> years later, found the Museum intact. The Bruchion library was destroyed <SPAN CLASS="small">A.D.</SPAN> 272; the Serapeum in <SPAN CLASS="small">A.D.</SPAN> 391. 400,000 volumes were destroyed in the Alexandrine war. See especially J. W. White, <I>The Scholia on the Aves of Aristophanes</I>, Introd.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note259" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref259
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">259</A>
In <SPAN CLASS="small">A.D.</SPAN> 272.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note260" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref260
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">260</A>
This included at least a fourth part of the city, and contained the royal palace.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note261" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref261
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">261</A>
The celebrated critic, born in Samothrace; he lived under Ptolemy Philometor (181‑146 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>).


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note262" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref262
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">262</A>
Also a grammarian.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note263" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref263
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">263</A>
This scholar (65 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>-<I>circ.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">A.D.</SPAN> 10) was surnamed <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">Χαλκέντερος</SPAN>, "of the brazen guts," because of his tireless industry; see also Index<!--</A>AMMIAN:INDEX-->.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note264" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref264
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">264</A>
Satirical poems; <I>cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Gellius/3*.html#7.4
	"TARGET="Gellius_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,EPlusL,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Gell. <SPAN CLASS="small">III</SPAN>.7.4 f.</A>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note265" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref265
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">265</A>
Wishing to represent himself as the equal of Apollo.
	<A HREF="
https://archive.org/stream/devitapythagoric00iamb#page/99/mode/2up
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Iamblichus, <I>De Vita Pyth.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">XXVIII</SPAN>.135, Nauck</A>, <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">τὸν μηρὸν χρύσεον ἐπέδειξεν Ἀβάριδι τῷ Ὑπερβορέῶ, εἰκάσαντι αὑτὸν


<A ID="p307x"></A>Ἀπόλλωνα εἰναι τὸν ἐν Ὑπερβορέοις, οὗπερ ἦν ἱερεὺς ὁ Ἄβαρις</SPAN>. This was one of the many absurd fictions of the Neo-Platonic writers.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note266" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref266
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">266</A>
<I>Cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/1A*.html#30
	"TARGET="Herodotus_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Herodotus,WIDTH,220)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Hdt. 1.30</A>, who says that Solon did not come to Egypt until after he had made his laws; see also Aristotle, <I>Const. of Athens</I>. The Romans are said to have made use of his code in compiling the XII Tables.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note267" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref267
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">267</A>
Of thought.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note268" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref268
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">268</A>
Or "gloomier than <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">magi</SPAN> are."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note269" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref269
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">269</A>
It differed, however, from other provinces, in being ruled by a prefect of equestrian rank. See
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#note251
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
16.6, note</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note270" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref270
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">270</A>
This Ptolemy is identical with (Ptolemaeus) Apion just mentioned, following, as the similarity in language indicates, Rufius Festus, <I>Brev.</I> 13. <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Cyrenas . . . antiquioris Ptolomaei liberalitate suscepimus; Libyam supremo Apionis regis arbitrio sumus adsecuti</SPAN>. Ptolemaeus Apion, king of Cyrene, died in 96 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>, but Cyrene first became a Roman province in 74 <SPAN CLASS="small">B.C.</SPAN>; <I>cf.</I> Eutropius, <SPAN CLASS="small">VI</SPAN>.11.2<!--</A>EUTROPIUS6-->, <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">qui rex eius</SPAN> (= <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Cyrenae</SPAN>) <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">fuerat</SPAN>.<!-- Loeb fails to italicize "fuerat" -->



	<HR CLASS="endnotes"><A ID="endnotes_T"></A>
	<H2>
Thayer's Notes:
	</H2>


	<P CLASS="a0 justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:malodorous_Jews" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref:malodorous_Jews
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">a</A>
For the whole question of whether Jews stink — an opinion current in Christian Europe for a thousand and some years after Ammian — see the rather detailed commonsense refutation by Sir Thomas Browne,
	<A HREF="
https://penelope.uchicago.edu/pseudodoxia/pseudo410.html
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Pseud. Epid. <SPAN CLASS="small">IV</SPAN>.9, <I>Of the Jews</I></A>. The good doctor — while mentioning Ammian — inclines that the unreasonable opinion proceeds from misunderstood Christianity.
	<P CLASS="i1 b0 a0 justify">
Our passage here is of interest, though, since it is one of the few such statements that does not appear to have been made under the influence of that religion. The only possible explanation (short of an interpolation in the text of Ammian, noting that the point of the Marcus Aurelius story is fractiousness rather than odor) seems to be that as a group and in their own country, Jews may have had different enough dietary habits from those of gentiles as to make their scent noticeable. I am told that natives of India find the odor of Westerners offensive, very likely for our diet high in beef and animal fat.
	<P CLASS="i1 b0 a0 justify">
Another possibility, detailed by David Rohrbacher in <I>Mnemosyne</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">LVIII</SPAN>.441‑42 (2005), is that here we find expressed the notion, current among gentile Greeks and Romans at the time, that Egyptian Jews were afflicted with leprosy and therefore foul-smelling; the idea is found several centuries before Ammian, in
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Manetho/History_of_Egypt/2*.html#Fragment_54.229
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Manetho, Frag. 54 <SPAN CLASS="small italic">ap.</SPAN> Josephus, <I>Contra Apionem</I> 229</A>. <I>My thanks to Prof. Rohrbacher for bringing his paper to my attention.</I>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:George_of_Alexandria" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref:George_of_Alexandria
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">b</A>
This unsavoury character (at least in Ammian's account), though an Arian, just might be the origin of our familiar semi-legendary St. George: see
	<A HREF="
http://www.ucc.ie/milmart/grgorig.html
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
The Origin of the Cult of St. George
	</A>
(at the excellent Military Martyrs site); James Eason
	<A HREF="
https://penelope.uchicago.edu/oddnotes/stgeorge/stgeorge.html
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
in his equally good pages on the saint
	</A>
follows Sir Walter Ralegh and thinks not.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:ibises_and_basilisks" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref:ibises_and_basilisks
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">c</A>
Immediately from ibises and their eggs we pass to basilisks. One gets the feeling that some source is being abridged, since the <SPAN CLASS="whole">relation</SPAN>&shy;ship of these animals (and their eggs) was intimate; for a first approach to this convoluted topic, see
	<A HREF="
https://penelope.uchicago.edu/pseudodoxia/pseudo37.html#b20
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Sir Thomas Browne, <I>Pseud. Epid.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">III</SPAN>.7: <I>On the Basilisk</I></A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:syringes" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref:syringes
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">d</A>
This is a fairly good description, and would seem to be a pretty distinct memory, of the later royal tombs not far from the Pyramids.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:geometers_rod" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Ammian/22*.html#ref:geometers_rod
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">e</A>
The geometers' rod (in the text: <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">geometrico radio</SPAN>) was not for measuring, but for drawing in the sand and pointing; see
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/secondary/DARSAG/Radius.html
	"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Daremberg &amp; Saglio, <I>s.v.</I> <SPAN CLASS="smallcaps">Radius</SPAN></A>, and the references there.



